  {
    "query": "What is retrieval augmented generation?",
    "answer": "Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) refers to a technique that combines a parametric language model with a non-parametric external memory. This external memory is accessed through retrieval at inference time, allowing the model to generate text based on the information retrieved from the external memory.\n\nAs described in the context, the term RAG was introduced in a 2020 paper, which is not directly cited in the provided references. However, the concept is further explored in various studies, including a systematic review on the application of RAG in healthcare for large language models (Amugongo et al., 2025).\n\nThe basic idea behind RAG is to augment the generation capabilities of a language model by providing it with an external memory that can be accessed through retrieval. This allows the model to incorporate information from the external memory into its generation process, potentially leading to more accurate and informative text generation.\n\nWhile the provided context does not offer a detailed explanation of the technical aspects of RAG, it mentions that the technique involves combining a parametric language model with a non-parametric external memory. This suggests that RAG aims to leverage the strengths of both parametric and non-parametric approaches to improve the generation capabilities of language models.\n\nOverall, retrieval-augmented generation is a technique that enhances the text generation capabilities of language models by incorporating external knowledge and information through retrieval at inference time. However, a more comprehensive understanding of the technical details and applications of RAG would require further information beyond the provided context.",
